## 1. Introduction

### 1.1 Purpose

This TDD specifies the technical implementation of three subsystems for Kiro SDLC Agents v1.0.1: 1. Checksum Management — TypeScript module for SHA-256 integrity tracking 2. CI/CD Workflows — GitHub Actions YAML configurations 3. Sync Tooling — PowerShell script for cross-repository synchronization

### 1.2 Scope

* src/checksum.ts — hash computation, manifest I/O, file status detection
* src/injector.ts — safe update logic with backup/skip/overwrite strategies
* src/extension.ts — VS Code command registration and UX orchestration
* scripts/gen-checksums.js — CI-time manifest generation
* scripts/sync-from-source.ps1 — cross-repo file sync
* .github/workflows/ci.yml — CI build pipeline
* .github/workflows/publish.yml — publish pipeline

### 1.3 Technology Stack

|  |  |  |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Layer | Technology | Version |
| Language | TypeScript | 5.x |
| Runtime | Node.js | 20+ |
| Platform | VS Code Extension API | 1.85+ |
| Build Tool | npm + tsc | — |
| CI/CD | GitHub Actions | v4 actions |
| Scripting | PowerShell | 5.1+ |
| Hashing | Node.js crypto (SHA-256) | Built-in |

### 1.4 Design Principles

* **Single Responsibility** — Each module handles one concern (checksum.ts = hashing, injector.ts = file operations)
* **Immutable Bundled Manifest** — Shipped inside VSIX, cannot be tampered with
* **Git as Source of Truth** — gen-checksums reads from git HEAD, not filesystem
* **Graceful Degradation** — Missing/corrupted manifests don’t crash the extension
* **Idempotent Operations** — Running inject/update multiple times produces same result

### 1.5 Constraints

* Extension must work offline (no network calls for checksum operations)
* Maximum 500ms overhead on extension activation for ~50 tracked files
* gen-checksums.js must use Node.js stdlib only (no external dependencies)
* sync-from-source.ps1 must use PowerShell built-in cmdlets only

